Re: Playmakers NCAA 11 Alumni Dynasty Rosters

So. Much. Fun!

I went out and repurchased NCAA 11 just to play with these teams and check out the effects of the re-rates. I played a full 10 minute game using the proposed sliders and settings and it was awesome. USC vs. UCLA. I lost 34-17, mostly due to a few poor decisions in the passing game.

In terms of gameplay, it felt really balanced on the field. Player differentiation was really noticeable.

For me, Allen felt very different from Bush and White. You could tell Keyshawn and Mike Williams were bigger, stronger forces than Swan or Morton. On defense, Lott and Browner delivered some monster kill shots.

For them, Aikman played straight from the pocket, though he didn't take many shots downfield. McNeill did a great job finding cutback lanes, and you could tell who was who on defense, especially Eric Turner and Ken Norton.

I really liked the ratings and sliders together--the relative speeds and strengths of the various positions felt pretty well balanced. These are gonna be a blast to play with till NCAA 12 gets its patches.

Is there a version of your sliders for NCAA 11 that's meant for play with the regular named rosters?

DJ likes this.

ARIZONA

Playbook-Arizona

Offense-Pro Style-(Run-55%/Pass-45%)

Defense-3-4

IMPACT/ALL AMERICAN PLAYERS

Trung Canidate

Set Arizona school record for career rushing with 3,824 yards in only three years.

Tedy Bruschi

Bruschi was a stud defensive end for the Wildcats, where he tied the Division I-A career sack record (52). By the time Bruschi left Arizona, he had amassed 185 total tackles (137 solo) and six forced fumbles.

Chris McAlister

He had an illustrious career at Arizona where he won unanimous All-America 1st-team honors and was an All-Pac 10 1st-team choice for 3 straight seasons. He is only the 7th player in college football history to return a kickoff, punt and interception for touchdowns in the same season. His 18 interceptions at the end of his Arizona career ranked 3rd on the school's career-record chart behind Chuck Cecil and Jackie Wallace.
